nravel here!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring shadow class behavior**\\n\\nI'm trying to figure out why the shadow class in the test output is considered just a test class, not part of the library. If I replace the library class in the test output, will the instrumentation still work? The coverage report shows many attempts not covered, but maybe they activate later. Could it be better to execute the original class in the instrumented library jar instead? I need to explore the natural path that calls class$ to ensure everything is covered correctly.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Investigating bytecode and coverage**\\n\\nI'm considering how older bytecode used class$ for class literals, but now Java 8 primarily uses ldc, which doesn't create a natural call. To address this, I think I need to generate a class in the same package that invokes the original package-private synthetic method. Right now, there seems to be an issue where the coverage isn't showing up. Perhaps it's because the shadow patched version is replacing the original. Should I remove the shadow for TrustAndKeystoreSpecImpl to ensure it uses the instrumented library class instead?\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Ensuring test compliance**\\n\\nI need to make sure the test doesn't use reflection \\\"directly,\\\" following the rules. Instead, I'll use MethodHandles and defineClass, as seen in the previous repo. It’s fine that the build.gradle helper generalization may still be relevant since it's used elsewhere. I think we can remove the trust output and focus on the essential calls. I also want to edit build.gradle to take out the trust shadow output and adjust the doLast call.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_gIT0VYLu9maiPqtKTTIiGtxJ|fc_087791355d2e1781016a01c7158194819eba84b1c0e56b5773", "name": "edit", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/io.rest-assured/rest-assured/5.5.0/build.gradle", "edits": [{"oldText": "    outputs.file(generatedDirectAccessCla